#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:4
msgid "How to capture warnings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:8
msgid ""
"Starting from version ``3.1``, pytest now automatically catches warnings "
"during test execution and displays them at the end of the session:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:11
msgid ""
"# content of test_show_warnings.py\n"
"import warnings\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def api_v1():\n"
"    warnings.warn(UserWarning(\"api v1, should use functions from v2\"))\n"
"    return 1\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_one():\n"
"    assert api_v1() == 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:25
msgid "Running pytest now produces this output:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:27
msgid ""
"$ pytest test_show_warnings.py\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-9.x.y, pluggy-1.x.y\n"
"rootdir: /home/sweet/project\n"
"collected 1 item\n"
"\n"
"test_show_warnings.py .                                              [100%]\n"
"\n"
"============================= warnings summary "
"=============================\n"
"test_show_warnings.py::test_one\n"
"  /home/sweet/project/test_show_warnings.py:5: UserWarning: api v1, should "
"use functions from v2\n"
"    warnings.warn(UserWarning(\"api v1, should use functions from v2\"))\n"
"\n"
"-- Docs: https://docs.pytest.org/en/stable/how-to/capture-warnings.html\n"
"======================= 1 passed, 1 warning in 0.12s ======================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:48
msgid "Controlling warnings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:50
msgid ""
"Similar to Python's `warning filter`_ and :option:`-W option <python:-W>` "
"flag, pytest provides its own ``-W`` flag to control which warnings are "
"ignored, displayed, or turned into errors. See the `warning filter`_ "
"documentation for more advanced use-cases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:57
msgid ""
"This code sample shows how to treat any ``UserWarning`` category class of "
"warning as an error:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:60
msgid ""
"$ pytest -q test_show_warnings.py -W error::UserWarning\n"
"F                                                                    [100%]\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"_________________________________ test_one "
"_________________________________\n"
"\n"
"    def test_one():\n"
">       assert api_v1() == 1\n"
"               ^^^^^^^^\n"
"\n"
"test_show_warnings.py:10:\n"
"_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _\n"
"\n"
"    def api_v1():\n"
">       warnings.warn(UserWarning(\"api v1, should use functions from "
"v2\"))\n"
"E       UserWarning: api v1, should use functions from v2\n"
"\n"
"test_show_warnings.py:5: UserWarning\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"FAILED test_show_warnings.py::test_one - UserWarning: api v1, should "
"use ...\n"
"1 failed in 0.12s"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:83
msgid ""
"The same option can be set in the configuration file using the :confval:"
"`filterwarnings` configuration option. For example, the configuration below "
"will ignore all user warnings and specific deprecation warnings matching a "
"regex, but will transform all other warnings into errors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:90
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"filterwarnings = [\n"
"    'error',\n"
"    'ignore::UserWarning',\n"
"    # Note the use of single quote below to denote \"raw\" strings in TOML.\n"
"    'ignore:function ham\\(\\) is deprecated:DeprecationWarning',\n"
"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:102
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"filterwarnings =\n"
"    error\n"
"    ignore::UserWarning\n"
"    ignore:function ham\\(\\) is deprecated:DeprecationWarning"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:111
msgid ""
"When a warning matches more than one option in the list, the action for the "
"last matching option is performed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:117
msgid ""
"The ``-W`` flag and the :confval:`filterwarnings` configuration option use "
"warning filters that are similar in structure, but each configuration option "
"interprets its filter differently. For example, *message* in "
"``filterwarnings`` is a string containing a regular expression that the "
"start of the warning message must match, case-insensitively, while *message* "
"in ``-W`` is a literal string that the start of the warning message must "
"contain (case-insensitively), ignoring any whitespace at the start or end of "
"message. Consult the `warning filter`_ documentation for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:130
msgid "``@pytest.mark.filterwarnings``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:134
msgid ""
"You can use the :ref:`@pytest.mark.filterwarnings <pytest.mark."
"filterwarnings ref>` mark to add warning filters to specific test items, "
"allowing you to have finer control of which warnings should be captured at "
"test, class or even module level:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:138
msgid ""
"import warnings\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def api_v1():\n"
"    warnings.warn(UserWarning(\"api v1, should use functions from v2\"))\n"
"    return 1\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.filterwarnings(\"ignore:api v1\")\n"
"def test_one():\n"
"    assert api_v1() == 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:153
msgid "You can specify multiple filters with separate decorators:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:155
msgid ""
"# Ignore \"api v1\" warnings, but fail on all other warnings\n"
"@pytest.mark.filterwarnings(\"ignore:api v1\")\n"
"@pytest.mark.filterwarnings(\"error\")\n"
"def test_one():\n"
"    assert api_v1() == 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:163
msgid ""
"You can also pass multiple filters to a single mark by providing multiple "
"arguments:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:165
msgid ""
"# Later arguments take precedence, matching warnings.filterwarnings "
"behavior.\n"
"@pytest.mark.filterwarnings(\"error\", \"ignore:api v1\")\n"
"def test_one():\n"
"    assert api_v1() == 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:174
msgid ""
"Regarding decorator order and filter precedence: it's important to remember "
"that decorators are evaluated in reverse order, so you have to list the "
"warning filters in the reverse order compared to traditional :py:func:"
"`warnings.filterwarnings` and :option:`-W option <python:-W>` usage. This "
"means in practice that filters from earlier :ref:`@pytest.mark."
"filterwarnings <pytest.mark.filterwarnings ref>` decorators take precedence "
"over filters from later decorators, as illustrated in the example above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:182
msgid ""
"Filters applied using a mark take precedence over filters passed on the "
"command line or configured by the :confval:`filterwarnings` configuration "
"option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:185
msgid ""
"You may apply a filter to all tests of a class by using the :ref:"
"`filterwarnings <pytest.mark.filterwarnings ref>` mark as a class decorator "
"or to all tests in a module by setting the :globalvar:`pytestmark` variable:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:188
msgid ""
"# turns all warnings into errors for this module\n"
"pytestmark = pytest.mark.filterwarnings(\"error\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:196
msgid ""
"If you want to apply multiple filters (by assigning a list of :ref:"
"`filterwarnings <pytest.mark.filterwarnings ref>` mark to :globalvar:"
"`pytestmark`), you must use the traditional :py:func:`warnings."
"filterwarnings` ordering approach (later filters take precedence), which is "
"the reverse of the decorator approach mentioned above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:202
msgid ""
"*Credits go to Florian Schulze for the reference implementation in the* "
"`pytest-warnings`_ *plugin.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:208
msgid "Disabling warnings summary"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:210
msgid ""
"Although not recommended, you can use the :option:`--disable-warnings` "
"command-line option to suppress the warning summary entirely from the test "
"run output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:214
msgid "Disabling warning capture entirely"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:216
msgid ""
"This plugin is enabled by default but can be disabled entirely in your "
"configuration file with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:220
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"addopts = [\"-p\", \"no:warnings\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:227
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"addopts = -p no:warnings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:232
msgid ""
"Or passing ``-p no:warnings`` in the command-line. This might be useful if "
"your test suite handles warnings using an external system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:239
msgid "DeprecationWarning and PendingDeprecationWarning"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:241
msgid ""
"By default pytest will display ``DeprecationWarning`` and "
"``PendingDeprecationWarning`` warnings from user code and third-party "
"libraries, as recommended by :pep:`565`. This helps users keep their code "
"modern and avoid breakages when deprecated warnings are effectively removed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:245
msgid ""
"However, in the specific case where users capture any type of warnings in "
"their test, either with :func:`pytest.warns`, :func:`pytest.deprecated_call` "
"or using the :fixture:`recwarn` fixture, no warning will be displayed at all."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:249
msgid ""
"Sometimes it is useful to hide some specific deprecation warnings that "
"happen in code that you have no control over (such as third-party "
"libraries), in which case you might use the warning filters options "
"(configuration or marks) to ignore those warnings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:253
msgid "For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:257
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"filterwarnings = [\n"
"    'ignore:.*U.*mode is deprecated:DeprecationWarning',\n"
"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:266
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"filterwarnings =\n"
"    ignore:.*U.*mode is deprecated:DeprecationWarning"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:273
msgid ""
"This will ignore all warnings of type ``DeprecationWarning`` where the start "
"of the message matches the regular expression ``\".*U.*mode is "
"deprecated\"``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:276
msgid ""
"See :ref:`@pytest.mark.filterwarnings <filterwarnings>` and :ref:"
"`Controlling warnings <controlling-warnings>` for more examples."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:281
msgid ""
"If warnings are configured at the interpreter level, using the :envvar:"
"`python:PYTHONWARNINGS` environment variable or the ``-W`` command-line "
"option, pytest will not configure any filters by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:285
msgid ""
"Also pytest doesn't follow :pep:`565` suggestion of resetting all warning "
"filters because it might break test suites that configure warning filters "
"themselves by calling :func:`warnings.simplefilter` (see :issue:`2430` for "
"an example of that)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:295
msgid "Ensuring code triggers a deprecation warning"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:297
msgid ""
"You can also use :func:`pytest.deprecated_call` for checking that a certain "
"function call triggers a ``DeprecationWarning``, "
"``PendingDeprecationWarning`` or ``FutureWarning``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:301
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_myfunction_deprecated():\n"
"    with pytest.deprecated_call():\n"
"        myfunction(17)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:310
msgid ""
"This test will fail if ``myfunction`` does not issue a deprecation warning "
"when called with a ``17`` argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:325
msgid "Asserting warnings with the warns function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:327
msgid ""
"You can check that code raises a particular warning using :func:`pytest."
"warns`, which works in a similar manner to :ref:`raises <assertraises>` "
"(except that :ref:`raises <assertraises>` does not capture all exceptions, "
"only the ``expected_exception``):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:332
msgid ""
"import warnings\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_warning():\n"
"    with pytest.warns(UserWarning):\n"
"        warnings.warn(\"my warning\", UserWarning)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:343
msgid ""
"The test will fail if the warning in question is not raised. Use the keyword "
"argument ``match`` to assert that the warning matches a text or regex. To "
"match a literal string that may contain regular expression metacharacters "
"like ``(`` or ``.``, the pattern can first be escaped with ``re.escape``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:348
msgid "Some examples:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:350
msgid ""
">>> with warns(UserWarning, match=\"must be 0 or None\"):\n"
"...     warnings.warn(\"value must be 0 or None\", UserWarning)\n"
"...\n"
"\n"
">>> with warns(UserWarning, match=r\"must be \\d+$\"):\n"
"...     warnings.warn(\"value must be 42\", UserWarning)\n"
"...\n"
"\n"
">>> with warns(UserWarning, match=r\"must be \\d+$\"):\n"
"...     warnings.warn(\"this is not here\", UserWarning)\n"
"...\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"  ...\n"
"Failed: Regex pattern did not match any of the 1 warnings emitted.\n"
" Regex: ...\n"
" Emitted warnings: ...UserWarning...\n"
"\n"
">>> with warns(UserWarning, match=re.escape(\"issue with foo() func\")):\n"
"...     warnings.warn(\"issue with foo() func\")\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:374
msgid ""
"The function also returns a list of all raised warnings (as ``warnings."
"WarningMessage`` objects), which you can query for additional information:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:378
msgid ""
"with pytest.warns(RuntimeWarning) as record:\n"
"    warnings.warn(\"another warning\", RuntimeWarning)\n"
"\n"
"# check that only one warning was raised\n"
"assert len(record) == 1\n"
"# check that the message matches\n"
"assert record[0].message.args[0] == \"another warning\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:388
msgid ""
"Alternatively, you can examine raised warnings in detail using the :fixture:"
"`recwarn` fixture (see :ref:`below <recwarn>`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:392
msgid ""
"The :fixture:`recwarn` fixture automatically ensures to reset the warnings "
"filter at the end of the test, so no global state is leaked."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:400
msgid "Recording warnings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:402
msgid ""
"You can record raised warnings either using the :func:`pytest.warns` context "
"manager or with the :fixture:`recwarn` fixture."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:405
msgid ""
"To record with :func:`pytest.warns` without asserting anything about the "
"warnings, pass no arguments as the expected warning type and it will default "
"to a generic Warning:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:408
msgid ""
"with pytest.warns() as record:\n"
"    warnings.warn(\"user\", UserWarning)\n"
"    warnings.warn(\"runtime\", RuntimeWarning)\n"
"\n"
"assert len(record) == 2\n"
"assert str(record[0].message) == \"user\"\n"
"assert str(record[1].message) == \"runtime\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:418
msgid ""
"The :fixture:`recwarn` fixture will record warnings for the whole function:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:420
msgid ""
"import warnings\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_hello(recwarn):\n"
"    warnings.warn(\"hello\", UserWarning)\n"
"    assert len(recwarn) == 1\n"
"    w = recwarn.pop(UserWarning)\n"
"    assert issubclass(w.category, UserWarning)\n"
"    assert str(w.message) == \"hello\"\n"
"    assert w.filename\n"
"    assert w.lineno"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:434
msgid ""
"Both the :fixture:`recwarn` fixture and the :func:`pytest.warns` context "
"manager return the same interface for recorded warnings: a :class:`~_pytest."
"recwarn.WarningsRecorder` instance. To view the recorded warnings, you can "
"iterate over this instance, call ``len`` on it to get the number of recorded "
"warnings, or index into it to get a particular recorded warning."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:443
msgid "Additional use cases of warnings in tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:445
msgid ""
"Here are some use cases involving warnings that often come up in tests, and "
"suggestions on how to deal with them:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:447
msgid ""
"To ensure that **at least one** of the indicated warnings is issued, use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:449
msgid ""
"def test_warning():\n"
"    with pytest.warns((RuntimeWarning, UserWarning)):\n"
"        ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:455
msgid "To ensure that **only** certain warnings are issued, use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:457
msgid ""
"def test_warning(recwarn):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    assert len(recwarn) == 1\n"
"    user_warning = recwarn.pop(UserWarning)\n"
"    assert issubclass(user_warning.category, UserWarning)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:465
msgid "To ensure that **no** warnings are emitted, use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:467
msgid ""
"def test_warning():\n"
"    with warnings.catch_warnings():\n"
"        warnings.simplefilter(\"error\")\n"
"        ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:474
msgid "To suppress warnings, use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:476
msgid ""
"with warnings.catch_warnings():\n"
"    warnings.simplefilter(\"ignore\")\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:486
msgid "Custom failure messages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:488
msgid ""
"Recording warnings provides an opportunity to produce custom test failure "
"messages for when no warnings are issued or other conditions are met."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:492
msgid ""
"def test():\n"
"    with pytest.warns(Warning) as record:\n"
"        f()\n"
"        if not record:\n"
"            pytest.fail(\"Expected a warning!\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:500
msgid ""
"If no warnings are issued when calling ``f``, then ``not record`` will "
"evaluate to ``True``.  You can then call :func:`pytest.fail` with a custom "
"error message."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:507
msgid "Internal pytest warnings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:509
msgid ""
"pytest may generate its own warnings in some situations, such as improper "
"usage or deprecated features."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:511
msgid ""
"For example, pytest will emit a warning if it encounters a class that "
"matches :confval:`python_classes` but also defines an ``__init__`` "
"constructor, as this prevents the class from being instantiated:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:514
msgid ""
"# content of test_pytest_warnings.py\n"
"class Test:\n"
"    def __init__(self):\n"
"        pass\n"
"\n"
"    def test_foo(self):\n"
"        assert 1 == 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:524
msgid ""
"$ pytest test_pytest_warnings.py -q\n"
"\n"
"============================= warnings summary "
"=============================\n"
"test_pytest_warnings.py:1\n"
"  /home/sweet/project/test_pytest_warnings.py:1: PytestCollectionWarning: "
"cannot collect test class 'Test' because it has a __init__ constructor "
"(from: test_pytest_warnings.py)\n"
"    class Test:\n"
"\n"
"-- Docs: https://docs.pytest.org/en/stable/how-to/capture-warnings.html\n"
"1 warning in 0.12s"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:536
msgid ""
"These warnings might be filtered using the same builtin mechanisms used to "
"filter other types of warnings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:538
msgid ""
"Please read our :ref:`backwards-compatibility` to learn how we proceed about "
"deprecating and eventually removing features."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:541
msgid ""
"The full list of warnings is listed in :ref:`the reference documentation "
"<warnings ref>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:547
msgid "Resource Warnings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:549
msgid ""
"Additional information of the source of a :class:`ResourceWarning` can be "
"obtained when captured by pytest if :mod:`tracemalloc` module is enabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:552
msgid ""
"One convenient way to enable :mod:`tracemalloc` when running tests is to set "
"the :envvar:`PYTHONTRACEMALLOC` to a large enough number of frames (say "
"``20``, but that number is application dependent)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/capture-warnings.rst:555
msgid ""
"For more information, consult the `Python Development Mode <https://docs."
"python.org/3/library/devmode.html>`__ section in the Python documentation."
msgstr ""
